Implementing Logging in a Node.js Application
This project demonstrates how to integrate the Winston logging library into a Node.js application to capture and persist various events.

Features
Lightweight logging with Winston
Console and file-based transports
Structured JSON log entries with timestamps
Separate error log and combined log files
Simple example usage in the application
Getting Started
Follow these steps to set up and run the project.

Prerequisites
Node.js (version 14.x or newer recommended)
npm (comes with Node.js)
Installation
Initialize a new Node.js project (already done in this task, but for reference):

csharp
git init
npm init -y
Install Winston:

css
npm install --save winston@3.11.0
Project Structure
css
.
├── .gitignore
├── package-lock.json
├── package.json
├── README.md
└── src
    ├── logger.js
    └── main.js
Logging Configuration
Create src/logger.js with the following configuration:

js
const { createLogger, transports, format } = require('winston');

const logger = createLogger({
  level: 'info',
  format: format.combine(
    format.timestamp(),
    format.json()
  ),
  transports: [
    new transports.Console(),
    new transports.File({ filename: 'logs/error.log', level: 'error' }),
    new transports.File({ filename: 'logs/combined.log' })
  ]
});

module.exports = logger;
Implementing Logging in Your Application
Create src/main.js and use the logger:

js
const logger = require('./logger');

logger.log('info', 'This is an informational message.');
logger.log('warn', 'This is a warning message.');
logger.log('error', 'This is an error message.');

logger.info('This is another informational message.');
logger.warn('This is another warning message.');
logger.error('This is another error message.');
Run the Application
Execute the application to see logging in action:

css
node src/main.js
Check the console output as well as the log files located at:

logs/error.log
logs/combined.log
Version Control and Ignoring Generated Data
Ensure you have a proper .gitignore to avoid committing generated data and logs.
A typical .gitignore snippet:
bash
# Logs
logs/

# Node modules (optional; usually not committed)
node_modules/

# OS files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
Note: The logs directory and its files are often ignored in version control since they are generated at runtime.

Best Practices and Next Steps
Consider rotating logs or using a more advanced transport (e.g., winston-daily-rotate-file) for long-running applications.
If you extend the app, you can add structured logging for different modules, contexts, or correlation IDs.
Keep the package.json scripts simple, for example:
json
"scripts": {
  "start": "node src/main.js"
}